on":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Kyong, Kyong Suk, Young, Chae, Chi Young, Hang, Kil, Rin, Sang Hun, Chang, Chong, Insoo, Kum, Sun Young, Yom, Young Hwan.  Cambodian Kiwan, Oeurn, Phoeun, Pich, Saroeuth, Seung, Sophath, Sophea, Yoeun, Phan, Son.  Indian Shanti, Harendra.","Indian (Uttar Pradesh): Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>om</i>, the Hindu sacred and mystic syllable uttered at the beginning of prayers.","Cambodian: written ឱម, corresponding to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Kirkhouse","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name, nickname from Middle English  <i>kirk</i> ‘church’ (Old Scandinavian  <i>kirkja</i>) +  <i>hous</i> ‘house, dwelling’, used for someone who lived or worked ‘(at the) church house’.  Compare  Churchouse  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Churchouse","meanings":["English: nickname, locative name from Middle English  <i>chirche hous</i> ‘church house’, a house belonging to or used by a church; a parish room, probably used to denote the caretaker of such a house, though he may also have lived there."]},{"name":"Kirkus","meanings":["English:  see  Kirkhouse  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Maxwell of Kirkhouse was born in 1552, in Kirkhouse, Cumbria, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Nicolas Maxwell. He died in 1583, in Salisbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1552–1583":"1552–1583","1554–1615":"1554–1615","1576–1650":"1576–1650","1576":"1576","1554":"1554","1552":"1552","1650":"1650","1583":"1583","1615":"1615","Kirkhouse, UK":"Kirkhouse, Cumbria, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Salisbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Salisbury, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Holyrood, Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1552–1583":"1552–1583","1554–1615":"1554–1615","1576–1650":"1576–1650","1576":"1576","1554":"1554","1552":"1552","1650":"1650","1583":"1583","1615":"1615","Kirkhouse, UK":"Kirkhouse, Cumbria, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Salisbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Salisbury, Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Holyrood, Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1552–1583":"1552–1583","1554–1615":"1554–1615","1576–1650":"1576–1650","1576":"1576","1554":"1554",